My PSA for the night: 
Number one activity one should NOT participate in before bed: looking up the sexual predators in your area. Not conducive to a successful night's sleep.
Just a little tidbit, an FYI if you will...&nbsp;
Counting sheep? Sure. Getting a snack? Great! Counting down from 100? It works!&nbsp;
Looking up the rapists in your area - not a good idea.

I'm very excited. Excited in a planet-humming way. Like some commercial where everything is in sync and you can't help but grin. Extremely excited. What am I excited for, you ask?&nbsp; 
We'll, I'll tell you. 
I have been searching for my dream. I know that your twenties are supposed to be this golden age where you really begin to discover yourself and get your fingers into a bunch of different pies. That particular task has been somewhat difficult for me, because - well, I didn't want to screw it up. I would concoct these ideas about where I was going to go to school and what I would study and the places I'd go and all of the fantastical people I would meet. These plans were eventually scrapped because I would let myself be convinced that it wasn't the right thing to do. 
I've been on this cycle since high school, and I'm tired of it. 
I've decided that I would rather screw up and do the wrong thing than waste my time doing nothing at all.&nbsp; 
I want to travel, and drink coffee in places I've never been before. I want to see&nbsp;foreign&nbsp;sites.&nbsp;I want to meet people I wouldn't normally have come across. I want to experience all these, and I'm excited because...&nbsp;I finally realized that it is something I have to do myself, and I'm perfectly willing to give it a shot.&nbsp; 
I suppose I got used to having things and events directed and planned out for me, in some respects. I moved out, I did the stretching-of-the-wings thing already, but it was always in my own town in a relatively safe environment.&nbsp; 
And now - I'm craving the unknown. I can't wait for next fall, when I go to New York. My body gets tingly and I can feel electricity in my fingers when I think about it. I'm not trying to escape from anything at home, I'm not being forced out, I'm not running away... I'm just ready for what is next, for working and living and going to school in New York.&nbsp; 
So - I'm excited.

I had to write about a lost love today. My "completely confidential" teacher explained the anonymity we would be treated with concerning the inner workings of each assignment.
But if he expects me to tell him about my love's tears and my love's fears, of my love's dreams and my love's grave, he had better not hold his breath.&nbsp;

I feel that if I let these things out, then I will forget them myself and he will be lost to me. And if I don't want to forget him, and how he made me dance.
